ce:section.ce:para:
Experiment 1 – A total of 13 jet flames were identified from the videos. After heating, some cells began to produce gases. These gases were released into the room through the ventilation opening area of the module. Some grey gases appeared after 5 min, but the first dense gas, observed by the infrared camera, was vented at 12:50 min (12 min and 50 s). The hot gases ascended quickly and formed a layer under the ceiling. The gas venting rate significantly increased after 13:50 min. By 14:30 min, the ceiling layer of hot gases increased in volume, reaching the door. Another dense venting of gases was observed at 15:15 min, and was accumulated around the module, rising to a height of 0.7 m above the ground. At this time, approximately 10 cells (cell numbers 10 to 20) were undergoing a TR process without exhibiting burning conditions (see Fig. 4). Electrical sparks were observed near the module's ventilation opening at 19:20 min. 10 s later, the diffused fuel gas suspended in air was ignited, causing a flame front to propagate rapidly through the gas cloud (see Fig. 6
g and h). This phenomenon is hereafter referred to as a flash fire, defined as the rapid, non-explosive ignition of accumulated flammable gases within the compartment, resulting in a short-duration gas-phase combustion event. In this study, the onset of the flash fire is identified by the appearance of the first jet flame, which was observed at 19:45 min. The upper smoke layer in the room began to dilute at 20:00 min, after which the burner was turned off (Fig. 6i). The cell-to-cell TR propagation contributed to combustion in the module. Following the first jet flame, a diffusive flame of 80 cm height was observed emerging from the ventilation opening (See Fig. 7
). Burnt materials, including electrolytes and plastics from the module's casing, were released through the venting area. This debris fell to the floor and continued to burn throughout the experiment duration (see Fig. 6i). The sequence of jet flames is summarised in Table 3, along with the corresponding Fig. 6. The fire was fully extinguished by itself at 90 min.
